man-Speaking Community in Ottawa / rPatzelt, Anke -- tHome and Belonging in a Semi-Diasporic Setting: Converts to 'Reflexive Islam' in West European Societies / rUhlmann, Milena -- tHome-Making: Space, Virtuality, Ideology -- tBeing Home through Learning Palestinian Sociality: Swedish-Palestinian Houses in the West Bank / rGren, Nina -- tThe Sanctification of Home in Late Medieval England / rKern-Stähler, Annette -- tConstituting Transareal Convivence via Portable Collection Books: Home and Belonging in Times of Uprootedness and Increased Mobility / rPelz, Annegret / Windsperger, Marianne -- tAt Home Abroad? International House New York and the Cité Universitaire in Paris: Cosmopolitan versus Diasporic Internationalism / rWeymans, Wim -- t"Unfortunately, there is no plural for 'Heimat' in German": Home and Belonging in German Naturalization Ceremonies / rJakob, Maria -- tBecoming an American: Rethinking the United States Naturalization Policy / rLi, Qianqian -- tChris Abani's GraceLand: Constructing a Diasporic Space in a Postcolonial Metropolis / rBauer, Annika -- tNo Place like Home? Conceptualizations of 'Home' in Salman Rushdie's "At the Auction of the Ruby Slippers" and Roshi Fernando's Homesick / rButter, Stella -- tNarratives of Belonging: (Hi‐)stories, Boundaries, Trajectories -- tBeyond the Hall: Diasporic Constructions of Home and Belonging in Beowulf, The Wanderer, and The Seafarer / rWagner, Ricarda -- t(Non)Autochthonous Origins and the Question of Home and Exile in Nineteenthto Mid-Twentieth-Century English and Hebrew Literature / rWeiss, Vered -- tGeographies of Home: Constructions of Home and Belonging in Contemporary Emerging Adult Fiction / rHertlein, Saskia -- tIt All Depends on What You Mean by Home: Metaphors of Return in Chinese American Travel Memoirs from the 1980s to 2010s / rAmato, Jean -- tToo Chinese/Too Cuban: Emotional Maps and the Quest for Happiness in Cristina García's Monkey Hunting / rGarcía, Elena Igartuburu -- tDiasporic 'Home' and Transnational Identities in Gail Jones' Five Bells / rKušnír, Jaroslav -- tGerman-Turkish Identity in Fatih Akin's Head-On: Transgressing Gender Boundaries, Redefining Home and Belonging / rEicken, Verena von -- tShared Pleasures and Strange Elisions: Three Types of Queer Ambiguity and 'Return-Migration' in Afrosporic Fiction / rZabus, Chantal -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex  aDiaspora studies has developed in recent years from disparate enquiries into diasporic phenomena in political science, anthropology, history, geography, and literary and cultural studies. Its emergence as a full-fledged transdisciplinary research field has been predicated to a large degree on an interest in questions of dispersal and mobility. Based on the proceedings of an international conference by the Marie Curie Initial Training Network CoHaB, this volume undertakes to shift the focus to phenomena of home-making and the articulation of a sense of belonging in diasporic contexts. Contributors from a broad range of disciplines discuss a variety of historical and geographical instances of diasporas, exploring the methodological and theoretical challenges posed by the subjects of 'home' and 'belonging'. Including an interview with Homi K. Bhabha on these subjects and the place of theory in diaspora studies as well as contributions by such central figures as Pnina Werbner and Ihab Hassan, the volume aims at offering a new prospectus of the range and potential of academic work on the cultural formations of diaspora.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aBelonging (Social psychology) 0aCollective memory. 0aHome in literature. 4aConstructions of Home. 4aCultural studies. 4aDiaspora studies. 4aPostcolonialism. 70(DE-601)1057642210(DE-588)4122192-8aHeimatgMotiv2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-5